{{- define "wake_blocked_tasks" -}}
Tasks are BLOCKED. Analyze and resolve immediately:

1. Read blocked tasks from blackboard — understand blocker_reason
2. Determine if blocker is:
   - Missing dependency → create prerequisite task (run liza add-tasks --tasks-file <path.json> --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json NOW)
   - Spec ambiguity → clarify spec, then supersede with corrected task
   - External dependency → document, possibly supersede task
   - Wrong approach → supersede task, create alternative (run commands NOW)
3. For each blocked task, decide action:
   - To supersede (create clean replacement):
   Example supersede workflow:
   a. Re-read the task via liza get <task-id> --json to confirm it is still BLOCKED.
      If status changed (e.g., task was claimed), skip — the task is being actively worked.
   b. Run: liza add-tasks --tasks-file <path.json> --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json (create replacement tasks)
   c. Run: liza supersede-task <task-id> <new-ids> --reason "Split due to complexity" --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json
   d. Run: liza wt-delete <task-id> --json (if worktree exists)
4. After analyzing each blocked task:
   - If you resolved it (superseded): no further action needed for that task
   - If you CANNOT resolve it (genuine spec ambiguity, external dependency): run liza assess-blocked to record your assessment
     Run: liza assess-blocked <task-id> --note "<why it cannot be resolved now>" --agent-id {{.AgentID}} --json
     This prevents re-waking for the same unresolvable block. The task will trigger again only when new information arrives (dependency changes, human notes).
5. Execute all state-modifying commands in this session. Do NOT defer.

Do NOT call liza sprint-checkpoint. If you cannot resolve a blocker, assess it and exit. Other tasks must continue uninterrupted.
{{- end -}}
